Looking at this problem, I need to prove the naturality condition for the inverse natural transformation. 

The key insight is that if η is a natural isomorphism, then for any morphism f : X → Y, we have:
- η.arrow X ≫ G.homF f = F.homF f ≫ η.arrow Y (naturality of η)

And I need to show:
- inv(η.arrow X) ≫ F.homF f = G.homF f ≫ inv(η.arrow Y)

This follows by taking the naturality square for η and composing with the inverses appropriately.

```lean
noncomputable def NatIso_inverse {α β : Type*} [C : Category α] [D : Category β]
    {F G : Functor α β} (η : NaturalTransformation F G) (h : IsNatIso η) :
    NaturalTransformation G F where
  arrow X := by
    have := h X
    rw [iso_iff_isIso] at this
    choose f hf using this
    exact f.inv

  naturality {X Y} f := by
    have hX := h X
    have hY := h Y
    rw [iso_iff_isIso] at hX hY
    choose fX hfX using hX
    choose fY hfY using hY
    simp only [Category.comp]
    have nat := η.naturality f
    have := congrArg (fun g => fX.inv ≫ g ≫ fY.inv) nat
    simp only [Category.comp] at this
    rw [assoc, assoc, ←assoc (G.homF f), hfY.2, id_comp, ←assoc, hfX.1, comp_id] at this
    exact this
```
